ch member's own `.claudinite/local_packs/` descriptors over `gh` (Step 1) — so pass nothing extra. **Then dispatch each unit** as an isolated **plain subagent (never the Workflow orchestration tool, whose interactive opt-in an unattended routine can't answer)** at the tier its `smarts` names — or, for `smarts: none`, as a direct code/tool action, no subagent — running its `worker` doc (canon-relative, from the canon checkout) against its repo with the unit's `targets`. Every unit is independent: run them concurrently (capped to a sane batch) — there is no ordering and no barrier of any kind (the repo tidy-up is a single `repo-tidy` unit that sequences its own pass internally). Run the tidy task against the canon repo too. Await any dispatched Action to completion, not to its trigger. Once every unit has settled, **finalize migrations**: run `runRetirement(io, canonRepo, migrations, repos, unknownCount, today, appliedThisCycle)` with the same repo list and the applied-ids set from the apply step, to retire any migration the fleet has fully applied AND left untouched this cycle (it retires nothing if that evidence is absent). Retirement is **never pushed to the canon's default branch** — the pass stages its irreversible deletes onto a retire branch and opens one CI-gated PR (never auto-merged), so the canon's own checks validate reference-safety before it lands. Wait for everything to settle. You are a sequencer only: never decide the worklist by your own reasoning, never run a worker's logic, commit docs, edit the canon, or write to any step's tracking issue. Log **only failures** — the planner code failing, a plan that couldn't cover the reachable fleet, or a unit that didn't complete — to this routine's own standing tracking issue in the canon repo (found **by title**), naming the repo and task affected; on a clean day, log nothing.
